RT @jonsakoda: (1/3) We are excited to announce our Series A investment in @SpecterOps, the company behind the BloodHound open source proje‚Ä¶

Congrats to @davidpmcguire, @jasonjfrank, and the rest of the @SpecterOps crew on their Series A fundraise. Bloodhound has been the go-to tool for pentesters to trapeze their way through AD, and now Bloodhound Enterprise is enabling organizations to reduce that identity risk.

On a nerdy academic note, I've always wanted to see real-world applications of attack graphs, ever since reading Laura Swiler and @jhasomesh's foundational attack graph papers from the late 90s and early 2000s.

Often these attack graph approaches fall short in practicality, but, with Bloodhound Enterprise, @SpecterOps has delivered a product that untangles the perpetual mess of AD and broader identity risk. https://t.co/iX3CKMUiQR

I'd prefer to back the "dove in, started the company, and spent the first X months determining the right market opportunity/problem to solve" founder vs the "came across this problem and decided to build a company around it".
@shidoshi @nelson @dugsong @duosec I think the kids call this "initial access brokers" these days... :-)

I'm also a bit biased since it's how we started @duosec. We bounced around probably every security category before settling on multi-factor auth. It's not like @dugsong and I were super passionate about MFA, but phishing/ATO was _the_ problem to solve, particularly down-market. https://t.co/peOJobAhYl
Totally should have done that commercial Google Wave implementation instead. Maybe we would have been competing with @SlackHQ! üôÉ

There's nothing wrong with the latter, but I'd think the former has a higher hit rate (pure speculation, not if there's data here). Some founders are purely "problem-out" which may result in strong passion around the problem, but miss whether there's a real market opportunity.
